  "prompt": "How early could we impeach a president Trump?",
  "response": "The U.S. Constitution outlines the process for impeachment and removal of a sitting president in Article I and Article II. A president can be impeached at any point during their term if the House of Representatives votes to approve articles of impeachment. The specific grounds for impeachment are \"treason, bribery, or other high crimes and misdemeanors.\" \n\nFor President Trump specifically, impeachment proceedings were initiated twice:\n\n1. **First Impeachment:** On December 18, 2019, the House of Representatives approved two articles of impeachment against President Trump, charging him with abuse of power and obstruction of Congress. These charges were related to Trump's request for Ukraine to investigate political rival Joe Biden and the handling of military aid to Ukraine. The Senate acquitted him on February 5, 2020.\n\n2. **Second Impeachment:** On January 13, 2021, the House of Representatives impeached President Trump again, this time for \"incitement of insurrection\" following the January 6, 2021, storming of the Capitol by his supporters. This impeachment occurred just days before the end of his term on January 20, 2021. The Senate trial took place after he had already left office, concluding with his acquittal on February 13, 2021.\n\nIn practice, impeachment can be pursued as soon as the House of Representatives deems it appropriate based on evidence and political motivations. It does not have to be at a certain point in the president's term, and there is no specific \"early\" limit other than the practical and logistical aspects of gathering evidence and securing enough support in the House for the impeachment articles.",
